args.content:
[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "text": "Welcome to the Dead ReLU Neuron visualization. Today, we'll explore one of the fundamental problems in deep learning.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "text": "The ReLU activation function outputs zero for all negative inputs, and the input value for all positive inputs.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 3,
    "text": "This red shaded region is the dead zone. When a neuron's input falls here, the output is always zero.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 4,
    "text": "Look at this example. When x equals negative two, the output is zero.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 5,
    "text": "The gradient, or derivative, of ReLU is zero for all negative inputs, and one for all positive inputs.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 6,
    "text": "Zero gradient means no signal flows backward through the network.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 7,
    "text": "During backpropagation, weights are updated using the gradient. The chain rule multiplies gradients through each layer.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 8,
    "text": "But when the ReLU gradient is zero, the entire product becomes zero. This means the weight update term vanishes.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 9,
    "text": "The result? The new weight equals the old weight. Nothing changes.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 10,
    "text": "The neuron is now dead. Its weights are frozen forever, no matter how long you train.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  },
  {
    "id": 11,
    "text": "Remember: ReLU dies when x is less than zero, which means gradient equals zero, which means weights never update.",
    "voice": "default",
    "speed": 1.0
  }
]

